    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1884-03-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1884-03-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="282"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <head>No. 282.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Phelps</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Lima, Peru</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1884-03-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 26, 1884</date>. (Received April
                        15.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 77.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Recently there was introduced in the assembly an
                    act declaring the contract with Henry Meiggs, for the construction of the Oroya
                    Railroad, &amp;c., to be forfeited, and directing the Government to take
                    possession of the road, plant, &amp;c.</p>
                <p>I wrote to you in No. 58, at some length, concerning this road and the Trujillo
                    road.</p>
                <p>I may state here that so late as 1880 the Peruvian Government recognized the
                    validity of the Meiggs contract, made a new one with the then representatives of
                    Meiggs, and gave the right of transfer to any parties whatever. The transfer was
                    made in accordance therewith. The contract has been complied with. The war and
                    the occupation of Lima and the line of the road by the enemy here, of course,
                    prevented prosecution of work in construction.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Article</hi> 7, as modified by the assembly, provides
                    “Property of the nation may be disposed of to satisfy the public needs.”</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I should be pleased to receive instructions how to proceed in the event of
                    forcible proceedings in cases where I consider the contracts to be
                    unquestionably valid.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S. L. PHELPS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
